74 - Search a 2D Matrix
Problem Summary

Given an m x n matrix and a target value, determine whether the target exists in the matrix.

Properties of the Matrix
Each row is sorted in non-decreasing order.
The first element of each row is greater than the last element of the previous row.

Example:

[
 [1, 3, 5, 7],
 [10,11,16,20],
 [23,30,34,60]
]

Target:

3

Output:

true
Key Observation

Because:

7 < 10
20 < 23

the entire matrix behaves like a single sorted array.

If flattened:

1 3 5 7 10 11 16 20 23 30 34 60

This is a completely sorted sequence.

Therefore, we can apply Binary Search.

Binary Search on Flattened Matrix

Instead of searching row by row, treat the matrix as a virtual 1D sorted array.

Search Space
int low = 0;
int high = rows * cols - 1;

Total elements:

rows * cols
Converting 1D Index to 2D Coordinates

During binary search, we get a middle index:

int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

Convert it to matrix coordinates:

Row
row = mid / cols;
Column
col = mid % cols;
Example
Matrix:

[
 [1, 3, 5, 7],
 [10,11,16,20],
 [23,30,34,60]
]

cols = 4
mid = 5
row = 5 / 4 = 1
col = 5 % 4 = 1

Position:

matrix[1][1]

Value:

11
Binary Search Logic

Get the value at the current position:

int value = matrix[row][col];
If Found
value == target

Return:

true
If Value is Smaller
value < target

Search right half:

low = mid + 1;
If Value is Larger
value > target

Search left half:

high = mid - 1;
Algorithm
Calculate rows and columns.

Set:

low = 0
high = rows * cols - 1
Perform binary search.
Convert mid into (row, col).
Compare matrix value with target.
Return true if found, otherwise false.
Java Solution
class Solution {
    public boolean searchMatrix(int[][] matrix, int target) {

        int rows = matrix.length;
        int cols = matrix[0].length;

        int low = 0;
        int high = rows * cols - 1;

        while (low <= high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            int row = mid / cols;
            int col = mid % cols;

            int value = matrix[row][col];

            if (value == target) {
                return true;
            }
            else if (value < target) {
                low = mid + 1;
            }
            else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }
}
